    An implementation of a simple linear probing hash table, with a tombstone-free deletion algorithm taken from _Algorithm Design and Applications_, Section 6.3.3. (Note that because we do not use tombstones, we cannot use the maximum insertion probe length to bound the probe length of unsuccessful lookups.) The keys (there are no stored values) must be 32-bit integers, which are permuted to form the hash codes (i.e., the "hash function" is reversible). This obviates the need to separately store hash codes or rehash the keys to perform operations which use hash codes.
